<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Gallup Survey: Moms Say
   `No Way' to Cloth Diapers
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS (HPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Mothers will recycle newspapers or car pool to
help the environment, but ask them to do without disposable
diapers and most say, "No way."
   That's according to a Gallup Organization survey of more
than 800 mothers with children three years of age or younger.
The survey was conducted at the request of the Diaper
Manufacturers group of the American Paper Institute, a trade
group.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The survey, conducted in June, found that only one in four
mothers was willing to switch to cloth diapers to help
improve the environment, though nearly three of four would
recycle newspapers, and about 45% would car pool or build a
backyard compost pile to dispose of trash.
   Gallup said most mothers cited health reasons for using
disposable diapers. Tops on their list were: Disposable
diapers prevent leakage (85% of respondents), keeps baby's
skin drier (83%) and helps prevent spread of germs and
disease (62%).
   The findings didn't go over well with the National
Association of Diaper Services, proponents of cloth diapers.
According to the association, the cloth-diaper business has
been growing at an annual rate of 38.5%. "Somebody must be
changing," said John Shiffert, the association's executive
director.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900904-0095
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900904-0095.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Daily News Unions
   To Ask Advertisers
   To Boycott Paper
   ----
   Patrick M. Reilly
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6A
</SO>
<CO>
   TRB LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- New York newspaper unions, locked in difficult
negotiations with Tribune Co.'s Daily News, will ask
advertisers today to boycott the newspaper.
   In a related development, the 10 unions are preparing a
citywide outdoor advertising campaign, using billboards and
city buses to attack what they say is the "anti-labor" stance
of Daily News management. The ad campaign is to begin next
week.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The call for an advertiser boycott against the tabloid
follows months of rancor at the bargaining table. The paper's
10 unions, representing about 2,800 employees, have been
working without contracts since March 30. Little progress has
been made, and tensions have escalated.
   The unions have publicly ridiculed Daily News Publisher
James Hoge, while Tribune Co. has prepared extensive
contingency plans in case of a strike, with replacement staff
from pressmen to reporters ready to step in.
   The unions have prepared, too, sending out two letters in
recent months to 75 top Daily News advertisers, asking them
to suspend advertising in the paper when they are asked. A
recent letter said that "we will be boycotting to force the
Daily News to abandon its anti-labor strategy."
   Large advertisers that ignore the boycott could feel the
wrath of the unions, said Deborah Friedman, vice president of
Kamber Group, a public relations firm that represents the
unions. Uncooperative advertisers will be targeted by union
members, who will pass out leaflets outside their stores
"telling people what the store is doing to hurt working
people," she said. "Hopefully it won't get to that point."
   John Sloan, Daily News vice president, called the boycott
"a pathetic attempt at disinformation and diversion. It's a
misguided campaign of intimidation and threats and coercion
against our advertisers."
   The Daily News has taken its own steps. After five of the
unions authorized strike votes, it advertised last spring for
replacement workers, attracting at least 15,000 applicants.
   It's unclear how successful the boycott will be, but if it
works, it will worsen an already difficult year at the
newspaper. The Daily News, like other major metropolitan
newspapers, is struggling with steady declines in local ad
linage. In the first half of 1990, Daily News full-run ad
linage fell 14%. The poor advertising market and costs
related to labor strife have led analysts to predict the
Daily News could have a loss of as much as $45 million this
year on revenue of more than $400 million.
   "The unions are directing their efforts toward business
people who have the same objectives that we have: to run an
efficient operation," Mr. Sloan said. "It's doomed to fail."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900904-0094
</DOCNO>
