<HL>
   International:
   Emigration in Hong Kong
   Likely to Jump This Year
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   HONG KONG -- Emigration from Hong Kong will leap almost
50% in 1990 because of fears of China's takeover in 1997, the
British colonial government announced.
   The government said 62,000 people are expected to leave
the territory this year, compared with 42,000 last year, a
jump of 48%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A government spokesman said emigration was expected to
level out at about 60,000 people a year, or 1,150 people a
week. In 1991, he predicted, 58,000 will leave the colony.
   Most of those leaving are members of Hong Kong's
well-educated middle class, who have turned this
1,063-square-kilometer patch of islands and peninsula on the
southern Chinese coast into an economic powerhouse. Their
departure has sparked fears of economic and social problems
in Hong Kong once China resumes control of the territory in
1997.
   Interest in emigration has skyrocketed since China cracked
down on a movement for freedom in Beijing in June of last
year. The crackdown convinced many in the territory that
China could easily break its promise to maintain the colony's
freewheeling economic and social system for 50 years.
   London's refusal to give its colonial subjects the right
to live in Britain had a role in stimulating emigration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900904-0087
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900904-0087.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Salmon Survive Oil Spill
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   XON
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<LP>
   When the Exxon Valdez hit the rocks of Prince William
Sound last year, there were predictions of a near-apocalypse
for Alaska's salmon industry. Well, this year's salmon catch
is coming to an end and it turns out it will be the biggest
in history. This news, running counter to the consensus, has
merited barely a whisper of attention.
   So far, the Washington Post reports that 40 million salmon
have been caught, far outstripping the 1987 record harvest of
29 million. Many of the salmon were hatched last spring in
the very waters fouled by the Exxon Valdez oil spill. The
rest were released from hatcheries in Prince William Sound
and swam through the same waters on their way to the ocean.
At the largest hatchery in the area, the number of pink
salmon returning to the sound this summer was double the
average of recent years.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Last year's oil spill apparently had little effect on the
growth of plankton in the sound, the main source of food for
young salmon. Salmon hatcheries report plankton growth was
better than ever this year.
   Dozens of scientists are studying the sound to determine
what lasting effects in other areas, if any, the oil spill
will have. However, in another example of how manic
litigation can muzzle progress, many of the completed studies
have been put under wraps by lawyers doing battle in damage
suits resulting from the spill.
   The Exxon Valdez tragedy taught the oil companies a
lesson: that if they didn't take greater precautions, they
risked the financial future of their firms. But the
environmentalists who jumped on the spill to justify their
philosophy of zero-risk to the environment have refused to
acknowledge that the damage from the Valdez spill was not
irreversible. Their credibilty among informed people will
suffer so long as they insist on promoting the politics of
hysteria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900904-0086
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900904-0086.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Ensign Bank Said
   To Be Insolvent;
   U.S. Takes It Over
   ----
   By Paul Duke Jr.
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6A
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Federal regulators took over Ensign Bank, a
New York thrift controlled by Ted Arison, chairman of
Miami-based Carnival Cruise Lines Inc.
   The Office of Thrift Supervision said Ensign became
insolvent because "poor underwriting, inadequate appraisal
policies and, to a lesser degree, the softening New York-area
real estate market" left the thrift saddled with a high level
of nonperforming assets.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As of June 30, Ensign had assets of $1.78 billion,
liabilities of $1.79 billion and tangible capital of negative
$174.8 million, for a capital-to-assets ratio of negative
14.48%.
   A spokesman for Mr. Arison said in a statement that Mr.
Arison was "shocked and outraged" by the regulators' actions.
Ensign was in the middle of negotiations with federal
officials to recapitalize the thrift and to bring it into
full compliance with regulatory requirements, the spokesman
said.
   "There are problems with the bank -- no one denies that,"
the spokesman said. "But the bank wasn't going to fold."
Under plans being developed with regulators, Mr. Arison was
prepared to add "substantial amounts of new capital" to the
thrift, he said.
   Ensign's president and chief executive officer, Alan
Master, said the move by regulators was a "terrible and
unnecessary loss not only to the American taxpayer but also
to the communities served by Ensign and to Ensign's
employees."
   In 1985, the thrift, which has 19 branches in New York,
New Jersey and Florida, began "markedly" expanding its
construction, land and commercial real estate lending, the
OTS said. Nonperforming assets increased from $16.2 million,
or 1.58% of total assets, on Dec. 31, 1985, to $174.5
million, or 9.14% of total assets, on Dec. 31, 1989, the
agency said.
   The OTS said a whopping $416.7 million, or 22.2% of total
assets, were classified as "substandard, doubtful, or loss"
as of March 31. Ensign had net losses of $38 million in 1989
and $34.4 million for the first half of this year. Since May,
the thrift had been operating under an agreement with the
regulators restricting its loan and investment activities.
   The institution will remain open under the control of the
Resolution Trust Corp., the agency set up last year to sell
failed savings and loans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
