<HL>
   Axel Springer Profit
   Rose 7% in First Half
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   G.SPR
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   FRANKFURT -- Axel Springer Verlag said first-half net
income rose 7% to 60 million Deutsche marks ($38.3 million).
   The Hamburg, West Germany, publisher didn't provide
comparable figures for the year-earlier period. The company
said it achieved the results despite its cooperative ventures
in East Germany, which the company said demanded considerable
expenses.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company said it expects the positive earnings
developments to continue in the second half. The company
publishes West Germany's largest mass circulation tabloid
newspaper, Bild.
   Sales rose 14% to 1.67 billion marks, with all of the
company's sectors contributing to the increase.
   Newspapers sales rose 83 million marks to 369 million
marks, while magazine sales climbed 34 million marks to 369
million marks.
   Springer, which has about 11,800 employees, invested about
102 million marks in the first half.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900904-0078
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900904-0078.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Time Off: Diversions and Excursions Sept. 4-17
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<LP>
   ART
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   International Center of Photography Midtown, New York:
"Man Ray/Bazaar Years: A Fashion Retrospective" documents the
groundbreaking fashion photography of Man Ray, the surrealist
artist. The more than 140 photos, many incorporating as props
sculpture by Man Ray and BUSY such friends as Brancusi and
Giacometti, are distinguished by both technical
experimentation and dramatic imagery. Sept. 7-Nov. 25. The
exhibit then embarks on a two-year world tour.
   For those who prefer a behind-the-scenes perspective,
beginning next month there's a 10-lecture series, "The
Photographers," with participants scheduled to include the
German-born Life Magazine legend Alfred Eisenstaedt. Advance
registration required; call (212) 860-1776 for information.
   Also premiering at ICP Midtown this week is "The Power to
Heal: Ancient Arts &amp; Modern Medicine." Subjects range from
Tibetan healers administering pills made from diamonds and
rubies, to capuchin monkeys helping quadriplegics in Boston.
Through Oct. 14. 1133 Avenue of the Americas at 43rd Street.
                                                                                                       

   National Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C.: "Kazimir
Malevich, 1878-1935" -- About 170 paintings, works on paper
and architectural models by this Soviet avant-garde artist.
Of special interest are Malevich's original set and costume
designs for the cubo-futurist opera "Victory Over the Sun,"
which premiered to boos and a hail of rotten vegetables in
St. Petersburg in 1913 and was then suppressed for years in
the Soviet Union. Fourth Street at Constitution Avenue NW,
Sept. 16-Nov. 4. The show then travels to the new Armand
Hammer Museum and Cultural Center, Los Angeles (Nov. 25,
1990-Jan. 13, 1991); and the Metropolitan Museum of Art, New
York (Feb. 7-March 24, 1991).
                                                                                                       

   Met Life Gallery, New York: "Saving Our Past -- A Race
Against Time" -- The World Monuments Fund marks its 25th
anniversary with this photographic exhibit examining the key
issues, such as pollution, confronting preservationists
today. The show highlights some of the WMF's most prominent
projects of the past quarter-century: the Church of St.
Trophime in France; the Church of St. Ann and the Holy
Trinity in Brooklyn, N.Y.; the Citadelle Henry in Haiti; as
well as major murals by Diego Rivera damaged in the 1985
Mexico City earthquake. 24 East 24th St., Sept. 17-Dec. 28.
                                                                                                       

   FESTIVAL
                                                                                                       

   The third annual Geraldine R. Dodge Poetry Festival
gathers well-known national and international poets for
readings, workshops, discussions, storytelling and musical
performances, most of which are open to the general public.
(Some events are for preregistered high-school students and
teachers only.) Participants include Bei Dao and Duoduo, two
leading Chinese poets now in exile; Joyce Carol Oates; Native
American poet Joy Harjo; and black poet Lucille Clifton.
Waterloo Village, Stanhope, N.J., Sept. 13-15. (201)
540-8442.
                                                                                                       

   New York State Big Apple Festival -- A bit of the country
comes to the city with this two-day indoor-outdoor event
glorifying the Empire State's most-harvested fruit and
country life in general. The riverside esplanade at lower
Manhattan's World Financial Center will be the site of all
kinds of apple-related events: For the kids there'll be an
animal petting zoo, hay rides, apple-bobbing and even piglet
races. For adults there'll be a wine and cheese garden and a
demonstration of grape pressing. For everyone there'll be
apple food products, strolling musicians, fiddlers, magicians
and the antics of a "Walking/Talking Apple." Battery Park
City, Sept. 16 and 17, 11 a.m. to 6 p.m.
                                                                                                       

   MUSIC
                                                                                                       

   Lyric Opera of Chicago: A rare staging of Christoph
Willibald Gluck's "Alceste" stars Jessye Norman as the
paragon of connubial fidelity and Chris Merritt as the object
of her self-sacrificing impulse. The production, by Robert
Wilson, is conducted by Gary Bertini. 20 North Wacker Drive.
Sept. 14, 18, 22, 26; Oct. 1, 5, 9, 13. (312) 332-2244.
                                                                                                       

   Opera Omaha: The fall festival gets under way with a bel
canto rarity, Donizetti's "Maria Padilla," starring Renee
Fleming (Sept. 14, 16, 20, 22). Also new is "Golem," a
setting by British composer John Casken of the Jewish fable
about a Frankensteinoid monster who goes beserk for lack of
love (Sept. 15, 21, 23). Filling other evenings with her
songs of Weil is Angelina Reaux, who brings her one woman
show, "Stranger Here Myself," to Nebraska (Sept. 13, 16, 23).
Witherspoon Concert Hall at the Joslyn Art Museum. (402)
342-7107.
