<HL>
   Pinnacle West
   Bid Abandoned
   By PacifiCorp
   ---
   `Power Swap' Is Set Instead;
   Pinnacle Utility May Get
   As Much as $260 Million
   ----
   By Jill Bettner
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   PNW PPW NVP
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<LP>
   PacifiCorp agreed to drop its pursuit of Pinnacle West
Capital Corp., ending a 10-month battle, in exchange for
seasonal "power swaps" with Pinnacle West's Arizona utility
unit in a pact potentially valued at $260 million.
   PacifiCorp would get about half the additional power
capacity it had sought in repeated attempts to acquire
Pinnacle West or its Arizona Public Service Co. under the
agreement. PacifiCorp had talked of a hostile bid after
Pinnacle West's board rejected its latest bid of $1.82
billion, or $21 a share, in May as financially inadequate.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A.M. Gleason, PacifiCorp president and chief executive
officer, said he would rather have gained all of Arizona
Public, making PacifiCorp the country's biggest
investor-owned utility. "But we made a judgment based on
economics and concluded this was a satisfactory alternative."
   For Pinnacle West shareholders, "this is a real shocker,"
said Edward J. Tirello, a utility analyst at Smith Barney,
Harris Upham &amp; Co. "It leaves them with a basketful of
promises and no money. I wouldn't be surprised if the stock
drops to $12 a share."
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading Friday,
Pinnacle West shares closed at $16.125, up 12.5 cents and
PacifiCorp closed at $19.375, up 50 cents. The power swap was
announced after the close of trading.
   During the weekend, Richard Snell, Pinnacle West
president, chairman and chief executive officer, said that
the pact doesn't include a formal standstill agreement with
PacifiCorp but that lawyers are drafting one.
   Mr. Snell added that further hostilities would be
"inconsistent" with the new rapport between the companies'
chief executives. They and aides crafted the power swap over
the past two weeks, working mostly at a Las Vegas hotel to
ensure secrecy.
   Pinnacle West, based in Phoenix, Ariz., is a holding
company whose Arizona Public is the state's largest utility.
PacifiCorp is a Portland, Ore., electric utility whose
service territories cover parts of seven states reaching east
from the Pacific Northwest to Utah, but which exclude Arizona
and Nevada.
   Analysts quickly theorized that Nevada Power could be
PacifiCorp's next takeover target. "I wouldn't speculate on
whether we would or wouldn't do anything beyond this
transaction," Mr. Gleason said.
   State and federal regulators must approve the 30-year
agreement, which could take several months. PacifiCorp would
gain a partial interest in two units of Arizona Public's
Cholla coal-fired power plant, giving it about 350 additional
megawatts of capacity during its peak winter season at
relatively low cost. Analysts said it is paying about $600 a
kilowatt hour to Pinnacle West for the Cholla capacity, far
less than the $2,000 a kilowatt hour cost of a new plant.
   PacifiCorp would initially sell back half of its Cholla
capacity to Arizona Public between May and October, when that
utility's power needs are greatest.
   After five years, the agreement would allow Arizona Public
to buy back all of that power during the hottest six months
of the year. The two companies also agreed to share some
transmission facilities.
   If regulators approve the pact, PacifiCorp would
immediately pay Arizona Public $220 million. It would pay
Arizona Public another $40 million over the next five years
if Arizona Public added more transmission lines.
   Although power-sharing is used by several Northeastern
utilities, "this is probably the first between regions this
far apart and with these kinds of climactic differences,"
said Mr. Gleason.
   Pinnacle West would get badly needed cash from the
arrangement for its plan to pay about $600 million of debt by
the end of 1993 and restore its common-stock dividend. The
company suspended its payout of 40 cents a share last October
in the face of mounting losses from its MeraBank thrift unit,
which was seized by federal regulators in January.
   The PacifiCorp pact "probably won't affect that
timetable," said Mr. Snell. But he added that Pinnacle West
will further reduce its requested rate increase. The company
revised its initial request for a 22% boost over the next
three years in June after unveiling a cost-squeezing plan.
The PacifiCorp agreement won't increase job reductions slated
in the plan for this year.
   Mr. Snell said Pinnacle West remains uninterested in a
$500 million offer by Salt River Project, a
quasi-municipality, for some of Arizona Public's transmission
facilities. A Salt River spokesman said that, as before, it
wouldn't pursue its offer aggressively, "but we need time to
analyze what effect this agreement will have on us. Other
utilities in the Southwest will be doing the same thing."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900904-0058
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900904-0058.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Boeing Co. Receives $6 Billion Order
   From Up-and-Coming Korean Carrier
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   BA FREST U.GPA MD NWA F.ABI F.ASP G.MES U.BA
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<LP>
   Boeing Co. received a $6 billion order from Asiana
Airlines, a new South Korean carrier.
   Asiana placed firm orders for 27 Boeing aircraft valued at
about $3 billion and took options for 24 other planes, also
valued at about $3 billion. The Asiana order, which was
expected, is for six 747-400 passenger jets, three 747-400
freighters, 10 767-300 jets and eight 737-400 jets. The
planes are scheduled for delivery between 1993 and 1999.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Separately, GPA Group Ltd. of Ireland, one of the world's
largest airliner-leasing companies, said it ordered as many
as 25 McDonnell Douglas MD-11 long-range aircraft, valued at
about $2.5 billion.
   McDonnell Douglas couldn't be reached for comment, but GPA
said the order comprises 13 firm orders and options on 12
more MD-11s, due for delivery between 1995 and 1999. Graham
Boyd, GPA's managing director for new aircraft acquisitions,
told reporters at the biennial Farnborough air show near
London that the company has no customers yet for the new
planes.
   Also at the show, NWA Inc. announced it had converted
options on 75 Airbus Industrie A-320 commercial jets into
firm orders and had taken new options on 30 A-321 aircraft in
a transaction valued at $4.6 billion. NWA, the
Minneapolis-based parent of Northwest Airlines, said it would
be operating 100 A-320s by 1995. It already has eight of the
150-seat short-haul to medium-haul airliners in operation.
Northwest said the new options for the A-321 were convertible
into A-320s before 1994 and were for delivery after 1996.
   Airbus, a consortium comprising Aerospatiale of France,
Messerschmitt-Boelkow-Blohm G.m.b.H. of West Germany, British
Aerospace PLC and Construcciones Aeronauticas S.A. of Spain.,
also announced at the air show that it may be profitable this
year, which would be a first in the consortium's 20-year
history. Managing Director Jean Pierson said "we might be in
the black" for 1990, on revenue of about $5 billion. He
declined to elaborate on the sum. Airbus had said it would
become profitable in 1994 or 1995.
   He said the consortium probably will receive 300 to 350
firm orders this year, down from last year's record 421
orders but above the 270 orders forecast earlier this year
for 1990.
   Asiana, South Korea's No. 2 airline, is moving quickly to
set up an international carrier network in the fast-growing
Asian region. Formed in 1988 by South Korean industrial
conglomerate Khumo Group, Asiana began by flying charter
services with leased jetliners. Emboldened by the
government's policy on airline deregulation, the carrier has
since moved into scheduled flights and began expanding
overseas last January. The Seoul-based company plans to
expand service to the U.S. in the fall of 1991, with other
routes through Asia. The company has grown so fast that it
had to lure pilots away from its well-established rival,
Korean Air, until Korean Air asked the government to ban the
practice. Asiana has a leased fleet of 10 Boeing 737-400s and
two 737-500s.
   Also at the airshow, British Airways PLC confirmed that it
has deferred decision on ordering new aircraft, partly
because of the Persian Gulf crisis. A spokeswoman for the
company, Britain's largest airline operator, said it was
originally due to announce around this time a decision on
replacing aging aircraft, primarily its fleet of eight
DC-10s.
</TEXT>
