<HL>
   Who's News:
   Rockwell Completes
   Group's Realignment
   And Names Officials
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   ROK WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. -- Rockwell International Corp. said it
completed the realignment of its defense-electronics group by
combining several businesses and naming new executives to
head two reorganized divisions.
   The realignment, which began in March, is designed to
allow Rockwell to bid more effectively on Pentagon contracts
and overseas work, the company has said. The latest moves
affect about half of the defense-electronic's group's 16,000
employees. Some of them may move, but there aren't any job
reductions planned at this time, a Rockwell spokesman said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   John D. Cosgrove, 55 years old, was named president of the
newly created Collins Avionics and Communications division
with about 5,000 employees in Cedar Rapids, Iowa. He was
formerly president of a business that is part of the new
division. Robert P. Marovich, 47, formerly vice president and
general manager of another business in the division, was
named its executive vice president.
   Ronald A. Kodimer, 55, was named vice president and
general manager of the newly created Command and Control
Systems division in Richardson, Texas, a suburb near Dallas.
The division employs about 2,400 people, including 600 in San
Bernardino, Calif. Mr. Kodimer was executive vice president
of another division as well as vice president and director of
a business that is part of the new division. Edward J.
Stephens, 62, was named executive vice president of the
division. He had been a director of another division.
</TEXT>
