<HL>
   International Brief -- Tokyu Department Store Co.:
   First Half Profit Up 14.7%;
   Firm Expects Competition
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   J.TDP
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
</IN>
<LP>
   Tokyu Department Store Co. reported that net income in the
first half, ended July 31, climbed 14.7% to 3.473 billion
yen, or 12.65 yen a share, from 3.029 billion yen, or 12.01
yen a share.
   Reflecting Japan's strong consumer spending in the latest
reporting term, overall sales registered 190.336 billion yen,
showing a 21.4% increase from 156.816 billion yen a year
earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the Tokyo-based company also is predicting some trying
circumstances ahead, such as fierce competition to result
from easing of the large-scale retail store regulation, which
enables foreign department stores to make inroads to Japan.
   For the full year, Tokyu forecasts that sales will reach
387 billion yen from 346.523 billion yen the previous year.
Net income is estimated at around 5.7 billion, up from 5.189
billion yen in the prior fiscal year.
</TEXT>
