<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   CHRYSLER PLANS TO EXTEND its cost-cutting efforts and
raise the goal to $2.5 billion, $1 billion more than
previously disclosed, Iacocca said in an interview. The auto
maker needs the savings to cope with a surge in
buyer-incentive expenses. The chairman also said the company
is committed to maintaining its current common dividend and
is looking for a European partner to cooperate on vehicle
development and distribution.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   PacifiCorp agreed to drop its pursuit of Pinnacle West
Capital in exchange for a power swap with Pinnacle's Arizona
utility unit in a pact potentially worth $260 million.
   ---
   Boeing received $6 billion of firm orders and options from
Asiana, a new South Korean airline. Separately, McDonnell
Douglas got $2.5 billion in orders and options from
airliner-leasing firm GPA Group.
   ---
   World oil supplies will remain adequate until October, but
tighter reserves are anticipated as winter approaches, a
21-nation group said.
                                                                                                       

   Alaskan oil output will increase more than first predicted
to help offset the losses of Mideast crude, the Energy
Department said.
   ---
   Stocks rose Friday in the slowest trading session of the
year. The Dow Jones industrials gained 21.04 points to close
at 2614.36. The bond market closed mostly lower in light
activity.
   ---
   Japanese regulators punished four firms, including a
Citicorp unit, for alleged roles in a stock-rigging scheme.
The move signals a tougher stance by Tokyo against trading
abuses. Each firm will have to close an office briefly and
pay a fine.
                                                                                                       

   Tokyo stock prices declined sharply Monday on rumors of a
new stock-manipulation investigation.
   ---
   First Fidelity contracted with GM's EDS unit to
consolidate the bank's software and data operations. The
10-year pact is valued at about $450 million and may set a
pattern for other major banking companies.
   ---
   Advanced Micro Devices is preparing to clone Intel's 80386
microprocessor. The move would break Intel's monopoly on the
chip of choice for new personal computers.
   ---
   Brazil and the IMF agreed to a new pact, although the
exact amount of money the agency will lend the country hasn't
been determined.
   ---
   Shell Canada won the right to develop the Caroline gas
field. The company's $719.2 million plan beat out a rival
proposal by Husky Oil.
   ---
   Business failures are up 11.7% this year, adding to
worries that the U.S. is moving toward a recession.
   ---
   Bristol-Myers agreed to buy a one-third stake in French
nonprescription drug maker UPSA Group.
   ---
   Average farm prices fell 1.3% in August from July, as a
slump in grain prices more than offset record levels for beef
cattle and milk.
   ---
   The Tisch family disclosed it acquired stakes in BayBanks,
Continental Bank and Equimark. Shares of the banking firms
rose on the news.
   ---
   Canada's gross domestic product fell 0.4% in the second
quarter, reversing 7 1/2 years of growth and raising fears
that a recession is at hand.
   ---
   The purchasing managers' index due out today is expected
to indicate again a weak economy. Friday's August
unemployment report is anticipated to be unchanged from July.
   ---
