<HL>
   Heard on the Street:
   Ethanol, in Wake of Oil-Price Rise, May Help
   Fuel the Fortunes of Archer-Daniels-Midland
   ----
   By Scott Kilman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<CO>
   ADM TX CPC
</CO>
<IN>
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
HEARD ON THE STREET (HRD)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<LP>
   CHICAGO -- Archer-Daniels-Midland shares have wavered
along with the rest of the stock market since the Persian
Gulf crisis raised the specter of an oil-shock recession.
   But if oil prices stay up, Archer-Daniels might have a
silver lining: ethanol.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Decatur, Ill., processor of agricultural commodities
controls about 60% of U.S. ethanol capacity, according to
securities analysts. Made primarily from corn, ethanol is the
fuel additive that was trumpeted after the 1970s oil shocks
as a way to extend gasoline supplies.
   The public's interest waned in the 1980s as petroleum
prices eased. But the ethanol industry was nursed by a
partial exemption from the federal tax on gas.
   Now Wall Street expects the ethanol industry's fortunes to
rise again.
   Even before the Persian Gulf crisis rejuvenated interest
in alternative fuels, Congress was mulling whether to require
several big cities to use cleaner-burning fuels, such as
ethanol blends, as a way to reduce harmful auto emissions.
   Passage of clean-air legislation might double the demand
for ethanol, figures James G. Joyce, an analyst at Prescott
Ball &amp; Turben in New York.
   The recent jump in oil prices increases the chance that
Washington will extend past 1993 the controversial tax
exemption on ethanol-blended gasoline. The exemption amounts
to an effective subsidy of 60 cents on a gallon of ethanol.
   Without the tax exemption, ethanol isn't cost competitive
with gasoline until crude oil prices are at least $40 a
barrel, according to an Agriculture Department study.
   "This could be the watershed event that could lead to
Americans realizing the importance of ethanol," said Clinton
O. Mayer III, an analyst at Bear Stearns in New York.
   In the short term, ethanol producers are already reaping
some gains. Ethanol emulates changes in the price of
gasoline. Since Iraq invaded Kuwait a month ago, the
wholesale price of ethanol has climbed by roughly 15%, or 20
cents a gallon, in some markets.
   Another windfall for ethanol producers is that the price
of corn, which is one of the biggest expenses of making
ethanol, slipped 6% in August amid forecasts for a good-sized
harvest this autumn.
   "The people in the ethanol industry are printing money,"
said Richard T. Gadomski, chief executive of Memphis,
Tenn.-based PSI Group of Cos., which builds ethanol plants.
   Archer-Daniels probably stands to benefit the most from a
boost in the ethanol industry because it is widely seen as
the lowest cost producer. It has state-of-the-art facilities
and, unlike some competitors, it can switch three mills
between ethanol and high fructose corn syrup, a sugar
substitute used by the soft drink industry. That flexibility
allows it to run its mills at full capacity.
   After Archer-Daniels, the ethanol industry gets small
fast. According to analysts, the second-largest producer is
Pekin Energy, a venture between Texaco and CPC International.
Pekin markets about 80 million gallons annually;
Archer-Daniels's annual ethanol capacity is 700 million
gallons.
   It is difficult for analysts to calculate ethanol's effect
on Archer-Daniels' bottom line. Ethanol generates less than
10% of its revenue and the company is tight-lipped about its
numbers.
   According to George S. Dahlman, an analyst at Piper
Jaffray &amp; Hopwood, Minneapolis, some investors use the rough
rule of thumb that, on an annual basis, the after-tax
per-share profit of Archer-Daniels increases by 1.5 cents for
every penny-a-gallon increase in the price of ethanol.
   An Archer-Daniels official scoffs at the formula, noting
that investors can't know the price of the corn the company
buys nor of the byproducts it sells.
   But analysts are intrigued by the possibilities.
Archer-Daniels's annual ethanol capacity works out to about
2.36 gallons for each Archer-Daniels share outstanding.
   To be sure, there is reason to be wary about any ethanol
play. Any jump in corn prices could eliminate profits, and
the Midwest crop is unusually vulnerable to a yield-damaging
frost this month because the wet summer slowed its maturity.
   Several analysts said oil prices would have to remain high
for several months before they consider revising their
earnings estimates for the company.
   Until then, analysts are recommending purchase of
Archer-Daniels for other reasons, such as the prospects for
increased exports to Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union, and
strong domestic demand for the company's vegetable oil.
   Mr. Mayer of Bear Stearns said he is continuing to predict
that the company will earn $1.85 a share for the fiscal year
through June 1991, up 13.5% from fiscal 1990.
   ---
   Archer-Daniels-Midland
   (NYSE; Symbol: ADM)

   Business: Agricultural commodity processor
                                                                                                       

   Year ended June 30, 1990:
   Sales: $7.75 billion
   Net income: $483.5 million; $1.63 a share*
                                                                                                       

   Fourth quarter, June 30, 1990:
   Per-share earnings: 40 cents vs. 40 cents
                                                                                                       

   Average daily trading volume:
   668,482 shares
                                                                                                       

   Common shares outstanding: 269.9 million
                                                                                                       

   *Adjusted to reflect 5% stock dividend to be paid on Sept.
17.
</TEXT>
