<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   BAGHDAD TOLD nations with citizens trapped in Iraq to send
them food.
   Although Baghdad permitted the weekend departure of
several hundred foreigners, including Americans, it then
balked at allowing more airlifts, and solicited food
shipments for the hostages. The Iraqi government also
suspended payment of its foreign debt, conservatively
estimated at between $30 billion and $35 billion.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. is expected to announce a plan to forgive much of
the $7 billion in military debt owed by Egypt, a stalwart
American ally. And in another move to shore up support for
anti-Iraq action, Bush will confer Sunday with Gorbachev.
Meetings between the U.N.'s chief and Iraq's foreign minister
were fruitless.
   A U.S. Air Force F-16 fighter crashed in southern Saudi
Arabia during a training mission, but the solo pilot bailed
out safely, the Pentagon reported.
   ---
   New Zealand's Geoffrey Palmer resigned as prime minister
after opinion polls indicated his ruling Labor Party would be
defeated in next month's elections by the National Party.
Palmer said he would be succeeded by Foreign Minister Mike
Moore, who will be the country's third Labor prime minister
in little more than a year.
   ---
   Soviets lined up for bread at stores across Moscow for the
first time in years, with many blaming President Gorbachev's
policies for shortages of a growing list of products that
includes tobacco, paper, cheese and gasoline. The last time
Soviets could remember long bread lines was under Premier
Khrushchev, ousted in 1964.
                                                                                                       

   A radical economic plan was presented to Soviet leaders
Friday, as Gorbachev and Russian republic leader Yeltsin
seemed ready to scuttle most of a prior plan that was
prepared by Premier Ryzhkov. The new package calls for
earlier deregulation of most prices, along with large-scale
privatization.
   ---
   The Phnom Penh government said the Khmer Rouge guerrillas
want to sabotage a Cambodian peace settlement and are
preparing for prolonged civil war. All four factions involved
in Cambodia's 11-year conflict are to meet tomorrow in
Indonesia to discuss a five-nation plan that would give the
U.N. the power to oversee a cease-fire.
   ---
   East and West Germany signed a landmark unity treaty
Friday covering the merger of their legal and political
systems after the Oct. 3 unification of the two countries.
The treaty, which included a compromise on German abortion
laws, is expected to be approved by both parliaments
following debate over the next few weeks.
   ---
   NASA began its third countdown for space shuttle Columbia,
scheduled for liftoff Thursday. Last week, communications
problems with the shuttle's $150 million observatory prompted
space agency officials to call off a launch planned for
Saturday. A fuel leak halted the first countdown in May.
   ---
   The South African government freed 11 African National
Congress prisoners, the first of many due for release as a
precondition for talks between Pretoria and the
anti-apartheid group. As many as 3,500 political prisoners
are to be released by the government over the next five
months.
   ---
   A study found that exposure to polluted air can provoke
life-threatening irregular heartbeats in people suffering
from coronary artery disease. The report is further evidence
that carbon monoxide -- an urban pollutant emitted in auto
exhaust and by industrial smokestacks -- is harmful to the
heart.
   ---
   Rebel leader Charles Taylor declared war on a West African
peacekeeping force in Liberia, calling it a band of foreign
mercenaries. Taylor's insurgent group has been battling the
4,000 soldiers since they arrived in Monrovia 10 days ago.
The troops have been welcomed by rival guerrilla leader
Prince Johnson and by President Doe.
   ---
   Somalia's president dismissed the East African nation's
prime minister and his seven-month-old government as
diplomats reported that fighting between security forces and
rebels was intensifying in central regions of the country.
Siad Barre, who faces severe economic and social problems,
gave no reason for his action.
   ---
   About 135,000 public employees began a planned weeklong
strike in the Indian-ruled sector of Kashmir to protest
alleged brutalities by Indian police. At least nine people
were killed in two days of fighting between security forces
and Moslem activists.
   ---
   Canadian soldiers encircled a handful of defiant Mohawks
inside an alcohol treatment center at the Kanesatake
reservation in Oka, Quebec. Earlier, the army bulldozed
barricades that were erected seven weeks ago by Mohawks at
the reservation, and at a second Indian settlement, in a
dispute over a land claim involving a golf course.
   ---
   Ethnic Albanians staged a one-day strike to protest
Serbian rule in Yugoslavia's Kosovo province. Tensions have
risen since Serbia dissolved Kosovo's government and
Parliament in July after ethnic Albanian deputies issued a
declaration of independence from Serbia.
   ---
   Japan's Premier Kaifu prepared for Soviet Foreign Minister
Shevardnadze's visit to Tokyo today by declaring that Moscow
must give back four occupied northern islands before it can
hope for friendship and cooperation from the Japanese.
   ---
   Died: Robert Holmes a Court, 53, Australian businessman
known for takeover bids, Sunday, near Perth, Australia, of a
heart attack . . . Edwin O. Reischauer, 79, U.S. ambassador
to Japan from 1961 to 1966, Saturday, in La Jolla, Calif., of
hepatitis.
</TEXT>
