<HL>
   Alberta Natural
   To Take Control
   Of Joint Venture
   ----
   By Gary Lamphier
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6A
</SO>
<CO>
   T.ANG PCG
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
PIPELINE OPERATORS (PIP)
</IN>
<LP>
   CALGARY, Alberta -- Alberta Natural Gas Co. said it plans
to secure control of its troubled magnesium production joint
venture with Houston-based Magnesium International Corp.
   Norman Wagner, Alberta Natural's chairman and newly
appointed chief executive officer, said the company expects
to invest a further 50 million Canadian dollars (US$43.6
million) or so to win an unspecified majority interest in
Magnesium Co. of Canada, the joint venture that operates the
plant at High River, Alberta.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Wagner wouldn't say by how much Alberta Natural plans
to raise its stake. But he said its effort to secure control
of the venture, which has been hurt by construction and
engineering snags since modest output began in February,
shows "our confidence and our faith" in it. He predicted the
plant could be profitable within a year.
   The 12,500-metric-ton-a-year magnesium plant, originally
conceived as phase one of a three-phase, C$370 million
facility ultimately capable of producing 62,500 tons of
magnesium annually, is currently producing "exceptionally
high-quality product in an appropriate volume, but we are
working our way through some start-up problems," Mr. Wagner
said.
   Magnesium, a silver-white metallic element, is mainly used
as an alloy for producing aluminum.
   He didn't specify how much of the plant's capacity is
currently being used. It was previously expected to reach
commercial production levels by the current quarter. "We'll
let reality determine whether we have the capability here of
developing full-scale production," he said.
   Rumors have circulated that the resignation last month of
Alberta Natural's former president and chief executive,
Douglas Fenton, was tied to start-up problems at the
magnesium plant. Mr. Wagner wouldn't comment. Mr. Fenton
couldn't be reached.
   The plant was built as part of an ongoing diversification
strategy by Alberta Natural, whose current core businesses
include natural gas pipelines, gas processing and specialty
chemicals. The company is 49.2%-owned by Pacific Gas &amp;
Electric Co.'s gas pipeline unit, Pacific Gas Transmission
Co.
   Despite problems with its magnesium arm, Mr. Wagner said
Alberta Natural still has "a very good chance" of matching
last year's earnings, before special charges, of C$26.9
million, or C$1.26 a share. He didn't offer a specific
forecast. Final net last year was C$23.6 million, or C$1.11 a
share, on revenue of C$366.8 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900904-0018
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900904-0018.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Orange &amp; Rockland's
   Rate Increase Is Tied
   To Conservation Bid
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   ORU
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<LP>
   ALBANY, N.Y. -- The New York State Public Service
Commission approved a three-year rate increase for Orange &amp;
Rockland Utilities Inc. that requires the Pearl River,
N.Y.-based utility to offer energy-saving programs to its
180,000 customers.
   The utility, which had asked for a $22.5 million, or 5.8%,
increase, will receive an increase of about $10.5 million, or
2.7%, for the first year. But in an unusual arrangement, the
increases for the next two years will be tied to the
company's success at improving energy efficiency and
providing energy-saving programs for customers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Traditionally utilities have increased profits by selling
more power, but "this new agreement separates company profits
from sales," says Laurence DeWitt, head of the commission's
energy efficiency and environmental programs. Now "profits
will be tied to the utility's performance in helping its
customers be more energy efficient," he said.
   Under the agreement, Orange &amp; Rockland will install
energy-saving devices free of charge for many of its
residential and commercial customers beginning in January. It
also will provide rebates to customers who install various
energy-saving devices such as high-efficiency motors and
non-electrically driven cooling systems.
   "The purpose of the program is to reduce the total energy
costs of both residential and business consumers," Mr. DeWitt
said. Consumers who participate in these programs are
expected to see a reduction of 2% to 10% in their monthly
bills.
</TEXT>
