<HL>
   Shearson Is Indicted
   In Ohio Case Alleging
   Broker Wrongdoing
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES (SCR)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio -- In a case alleging stockbroker
wrongdoing before the 1987 stock-market crash, a state grand
jury issued 42 indictments each against Shearson Lehman
Brothers Inc., a former top Shearson broker in Cleveland and
the broker's former branch manager.
   The indictments charge the broker, Sheldon Strauss, with
fraud and false representation in the sale of securities. The
state said Mr. Strauss's clients suffered extensive losses in
the 1987 crash because of "heavily margined, speculative and
unauthorized investments" he made "with the full knowledge of
his supervisors at Shearson Lehman."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The former branch manager, Stephen Weinberg, and Shearson
were also named in the indictments for their alleged
complicity in Mr. Strauss's actions, the state said.
   Shearson, a New York-based brokerage concern, has already
settled more than $4.9 million of claims with Mr. Strauss's
former clients, the state said.
   A spokesman for Shearson, a unit of New York-based
American Express Co., said allegations that Shearson had
complicity are "totally without merit," even though the
alleged activity "didn't serve the best interest" of its
clients.
   The spokesman said the Messrs. Strauss and Weinberg no
longer work for Shearson -- Shearson dismissed Mr. Strauss in
late 1987 and Mr. Weinberg resigned in early 1988 -- and
noted that the alleged activity occured nearly three years
ago.
   In magazine and newspaper interviews over the past several
months, Mr. Strauss has acknowledged wiping out himself and
his clients in the 1987 stock crash, but he said Shearson is
as much to blame as him. He has said he wanted to "devote
whatever meager resources I have" to help investors sue their
brokerage firms in cases of improper sales techniques.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900904-0001
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900904-0001.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Apex Oil Emerges
   From Chapter 11
   As Leaner Concern
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
OIL, SECONDARY (OIS)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<LP>
   ST. LOUIS, Mo. -- Apex Oil Co. emerged from Chapter 11
bankruptcy proceedings, significantly smaller than when it
filed for protection from creditors on Christmas Eve, 1987.
   The closely held concern grew from a tiny oil-trading and
transportation operation to become, partly through its highly
leveraged 1981 acquisition of Clark Oil &amp; Refining Co., a
petroleum conglomerate with annual revenue of about $13
billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But after the company had big losses in oil futures
trading, and the value of its oil inventory tumbled because
of the petroleum market's mid-decade slump, Apex's lenders
pulled the plug on vital loan agreements.
   Apex cleared its debts with secured lenders in full in
1988, by selling its Clark Oil unit to a partnership composed
of Horsham Corp., Toronto, and Apex owners Paul A. Novelly
and Samuel R. Goldstein.
   Under the court-approved reorganization, Messrs. Goldstein
and Novelly will together lend $15 million to Apex. Banque
Indosuez of Geneva and Banque Paribas of New York each loaned
Apex $15 million in the reorganization.
   Apex's unsecured holders will receive as much as $20
million in cash, $20 million in seven-year notes secured by
Apex assets to be sold over two years, and $20 million in
10-year notes secured by a portion of anticipated profits
from Clark Oil Trading Co. Clark Oil Trading, owned by
Messrs. Novelly &amp; Goldstein, isn't associated with the bigger
Clark Oil &amp; Refining unit that was sold, nor did it ever come
under Chapter 11 protection.
   The settlement with unsecured debtholders represents
payment of 64 cents to 86 cents on the dollar.
   Apex, which said it operated profitably throughout the
Chapter 11 period, now plans to focus on its oil trading, oil
terminal and shipping operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900904-0149
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900904-0149.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
08/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   OIL PRICES ROSE on renewed worry that the Mideast crisis
might not be resolved soon enough to prevent tight supplies.
The price of refined petroleum rose faster than that of
crude. Gasoline futures gained 4.35 cents a gallon, while
crude jumped 85 cents a barrel to $26.77.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stock and bond prices sank, driven down by oil's rebound.
The Dow Jones industrials fell 39.11 points in thin trading
to 2593.32, as program trading helped trigger a late
sell-off. Long-term Treasury's lost about half a point. The
dollar strengthened.
   ---
   Tokyo stocks rose sharply as investors took in stride an
increase in the Bank of Japan's discount rate. The Nikkei
jumped 775.17 points, or 3.1%, on Thursday and gained a
further 244.49 points early Friday.
                                                                                                       

   Japan's discount-rate boost could sour the world economy
by forcing higher rates elsewhere, analysts say.
   ---
   Stock fund sales collapsed in August, posting their worst
month since the 1987 crash, as many investors shifted into
money market funds.
   ---
   Airline reservation systems ground into gridlock Wednesday
as a flood of callers tried to book cheap fares before the
prices went up.
   ---
   Mideast investors moved as much as $8 billion in capital
to the West after Iraq invaded Kuwait. Big U.S. banks are the
main beneficiaries.
   ---
   The number of S&amp;Ls described by regulators as
well-capitalized and profitable fell 7% in the first quarter.
   ---
   Hanson PLC plans to cut its stake in Newmont Mining to as
low as 26% from 49% through a public offering of shares in
the U.S. gold-mining firm.
   ---
   Lockheed shareholder Harold Simmons continues to press for
an increased stake in the company despite losing a proxy
battle this year.
   ---
   Factory orders rose 1.6% in July, nearly making up for a
1.9% drop in June. Aircraft orders were particularly strong,
while autos were weak.
   ---
   The Canadian and Hong Kong groups who agreed last month to
buy Columbia S&amp;L's $3 billion junk-bond portfolio may back
out of the deal if the U.S. economy worsens further.
   ---
   Campeau's Federated unit is challenging $586.8 million in
IRS claims. Separately, National Bank of Canada is taking a
$70.1 million provision against loans to Robert Campeau.
   ---
   Four big California utilities will be able to profit from
savings generated by their conservation efforts under a plan
approved by state regulators.
   ---
   The Labor Department launched a program to reduce arm and
wrist injuries and other disorders that are common in
repeated-motion jobs.
   ---
   Korean officials proposed legislation aimed at reversing
the Seoul stock market's 16-month slide. But prices sank on
the announcement.
   ---
   Gannett named Gary L. Watson, formerly head of the
community newspapers division, to run the firm's newly
consolidated newspaper group.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 120,890,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2593.32, off 39.11; transportation 901.26, off 9.87;
utilities 193.72, off 1.89.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3336.98,
off 10.19.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.23, up 0.17; spot
index 130.79, up 0.09.
   Dollar: 144.35 yen, up 0.75; 1.5640 marks, up 0.0045.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
